nit of the 70th Infantry Di\nvision and more than 700 WACS.\nSix other troop-carrying vessel*\nare scheduled to dock today at East\nCoast ports and three are due or\nthe West Coast.\nAlso the Swedish liner Gripsholrr\nwill dock at Jersey City with mori\nthan 1,500 civilian passengers fron\nPalestine, Greece, Egypt and Italy\nShips and Army units arriving:\nAt New York\u2014In addition to thi\nQueen Elizabeth\u2014(Aboard Oneidi\nVictory, from Le Havre) 1,954 mis\ncellaneous troops. (Aboard thi\nJohn Ericsson) 6,180 troops, undes\nignated units.\nAt Newport News\u2014(Aboard Elgii\nVictory) 1,963 miscellaneous person\nnel. (Aboard Marine Devil) 2,721\ntroops, including Headquarters am\nHeadquarters Company C, Commam\nB, of the 9th Armored Division\n400th armored Field Artillery Bat\ntalion, 73d Armored Field Artiller;\nBattalion, 19th Tank Battalion, 2(\nArmour Medical Battalion, 149tl\nArmored Signal Company and mis\ncellaneous personnel. (Aboard Le\njeune) 4,623 troops, including thi\nfollowing units of the 7th Armorei\nDivision: Headquarters and Head\nquarters Company, Reserve Com\nmand; Headquarters and Headquar\nters Company G. Command A\nHeadquarters and Headquarter\nBattery Division, Headquarters an<\nHeadquarters Trains Company an<\nMilitary Police Platoon.\nAt Boston\u2014(Aboard Sedalia Vic\ntory) 1,955 troops, including thi\n3,221st and 3,222d Signal Photo Pro\nduction Detachments, 3,243d Signa\nNewsreel Detachment, high scor<\npersonnel and casuals.\nAt Seattle\u2014(Aboard the C. F\nHughes) 2,000 troops, including 401\nformer prisoners of war. (Aboari\nthe Kola Agoeng) 1,561 troops, in\neluding some Navy and Coast Guan\npersonnel from Manila. (Aboard G\nD. Spurgis) 2.060 troops, undesig\nnated units.\nPolio Total Reaches 209\nWith Two New Cases\nTwo new cases of infantile para\nlysis were reported today to th\nHealth Department, bringing th\ntotal in the Metropolitan Area thi\nyear to 209, compared with 288 las\nyear.\nThe new cases are a 10-year\nold girl from the 4600 block o\nHilltop terrace S.E. and a 9 'i-year\nold boy from Nokesville, Va. Botl\nare at Children\u2019s Hospital.\nParliament\n(Continued From First Page.)\ndon Conference of Foreign Ministers\nThe affable Secretary Byrnes, a\nhome in the committee room, filler\nin the blank spaces of his Frida;\nnight radio report tq the Nation.\nTalked Senatorial Language.\nMembers said he gave them abou\nthe frankest, most detailed descrip\ntion of what went on behind th\nscenes at London that they had eve\nreceived about any conference,\ni Talking senatorial language, M\ni Byrnes was reported to have gotte\ndown to the brass tacks of what h\njsaid to Russian Foreign Commissa\nMolotov and what Mr. Moloto\nreplied.\nThe Senators liked the repor\nAnd they liked Secretary Byrne;\naction in permitting the conferenc\nto end in outward failure becaus\nhe would not agree to exclude Franc\nand China from discussions\u2019 of pro\nposed European treaties.\nLa Follette Commends Action.\nAs examples of their comment t\nreporters:\nSenator La Follette, Progressiv<\nof Wisconsin, often critical of ad\nministration foreign policy, sai\nSecretary Byrnes was to be com\nmended for \u201chaving made ever\neffort to react an agreement, shoi\nof compromising fundamental prin\nciples.\u201d\nSenator George, Democrat, c\nGeorgia, said he believed the entir\ncommittee approved of Secretar\nByrnes\u2019 course at London.\nSenator Lucas, Democrat, of 111!\nnols, asserted: \u201cHe has my com\nplete \u2019support.\u201d\nNext Move Up to Russia.\nCommittee members came awa\nfrom the meeting with the impres\nsion that the next move is up t\nRussia, and that Secretary Byrne\nremains hopeful of a later agree\nment.\nThe Secretary said in his radi\nspeech last week that as the recor\nstands Mr. Molctov had not re\njected an American proposal fc\na general peace conference at whic\nall the directly involved Allie\nwould participate.\nSenators got the idea that thi\nis being mulled over in Mosco\u2019\nand that there might be somethin\ncoming out of that caoital soon.\nArgentina Discussed Briefly.\nThe Argentine situation reported\nly was discussed only briefly.\nSome members had complaine\nthat the State Department acte\nhastily and single-handedly in get\nting the Rio de Janeiro Inter-Amei\nican Conference, scheduled for Oc\ntober 20, called off.\nMr. Byrnes was reported to ha\\\ndefended this course.\nThe committee will talk som\nmore about this phase of foreig\nrelations when it meets again tc\nmorrow to consider the nominatio\nof Spruille Braden, former Ambas\nsador to Buenos Aires, to be As\ni )Sistant Secretary of State.\nMeanwhile, the military regim\nin Argentina appears the loser in\nshrewd attempt to gain prestige b\ntaking advantage of weakened unit\namong the great powers.\nA bid by Juan Peron, dictator an\nvice president of Argentina, for ret\nognition by Russia is reported o\nexcellent authority to have been rt\nbuffed coldly by Moscow.\nThe HOME BUILDING ASS\u2019N\nOffers Courteous Help\nin Solving Your Real Estate\nLoan Problems. Expense of\nLoans Kept to a Minimum.\nNo Commissions Charged.\nCurrent Interest Rates.\nPrompt Action.\nLet Us Serve You\n2006 Pa. Ave. N.W., BE. 0250\nLi. f7. gj rAULina iturr.\n\u2014AP Wirephoto.\n\nAutopsy Report Made\nIn Hotel Room Death\nNew York police said today that\na preliminary autopsy showed that\nLt. John Gerald Mooney, 37-year\n1 old Washington naval officer who\nwas found dead yesterday in a New\nYork hotel room, died of general\ncongestion of the intestinal organs,\nthe Associated Press reported.\nDr. Milton Helpern, assistant\nmedical examiner, said this could\nhave resulted from an overdose ol\nsleeping tablets. Police found sev\n_ eral bottles of pills and an envelope\ncontaining 45 tablets in the room.\nWAVE Lt. (j. g.) Pauline Eliza\nbeth* Rupp, 34, who was found un\nI conscious in the room with Lt\nj Mooney, today regained conscious\nneess at Bellevue Hospital, but phv\nsicians said she still was in a crit\n1 ical condition and she was not ques\nI tioned immediately.\nBoth lieutenants were physicians\nPolice said they became acquaintec\nin St. Alban\u2019s Naval Hospital ir\nQueens several months ago.\nComplete findings of the autopsy\nI on Lt. Mooney will not be availabh\nfor five days, but New York polici\nsaid there was \u201cnothing suspicious\u2019\nand there will be no investigatior\nj by the homicide division unless th<\nManhattan medical examiner re\nquests one.\nLt. Mooney's wife, who lives al\n336 Thirty-sixth street N.E., said sh<\nwas convinced that her husband'!\ndeath was accidental. She said hei\nhusband had no cause for suicidf\nand it was probable that he acci\ndentally took too many pills. Mrs\nMooney said her husband took sleep\nS ing pills regularly.\nFulbright Reported Choice\nAs Head of Columbia U.\nEy the Associated Press,\nt NEW YORK. Oct. 9.\u2014The World\nTelegram said today that Senatoi\nFulbright, Democrat, of Arkansas\nmay become president of Columbit\nUniversity to succeed Dr. Nicholas\nMurray Butler, retired.\n\u201cThe Senator is the first choici\nof the Faculty Committee appointee\nto recommend a successor to Dr\nButler,\u201d the paper said. The uni\nt; versity\u2019s secretarial office refusec\n1; comment.\ni j \"The committee of the board o\ntrustees has taken no action,\u201d th\npaper quoted Frederick Coykendall\nti chairman of the Columbia Board o\nTrustees, as saying, \"and probabl;\nE won\u2019t for some time.\u201d\nr Senator Fulbright. 40, formerl\npresident of the University of Ar\nkansas, was elected to the Senate it\n3' 1943.\n^County, City Rule May Go\nTo Germans by Nov. 15\n0 By the Associated Press.\nE: BERLIN, Oct. 9.\u2014So rapidly 1\nE denazification of the American oc\ncupation zone in Germany proceed\ning that it may be possible to turi\nroutine administration of county an\ncity governments over to Germa;\n3 civil officials by November 15, ac\ncording to Gen. Eisenhower's head\nquarters.\nKrug Predicts End\nOf Production Slump\nBy Early 1946\nBy MALCOLM LAMBORNE, Jr.\nWar Production Board Chairman\nJ. A. Krug predicted today that the\ndecline in industrial paoduction and\nnational income will be halted by\nearly 1946 and that the United\nStates will complete the transition\nfrom war to peace late next year,\nassuming reconversion progresses in\nan orderly manner.\nThe forecasts wefe outlined in a\nlengthy report made today at the\n100th meeting of the War Produc\ntion Board. Mr. Krug will retire\nfrom Government service November\n3, at which time WPB will be liqui\ndated and replaced by the Civilian\nProduction Administration.\nMr. Krug also made public here\ntofore confidential figures on the\nNation\u2019s munitions output from\nJuly, 1940, to July of this year.\nIn that period, he disclosed, Amer\nican industry produced $186,000,000,\n000 worth of war materials, includ\ning a fleet of 297,000 military planes,\n76,485 ships, 17,400,000 rifles, car\nbines and sidearms, 41,400,000,000\nrounds of small arms ammunition\n4,200,000 tons of artillery shells, 86,\n338 tanks and 2,434,553 trucks.\nsubject to Modification.\nMr. Krug cautioned that his fore\ncasts for the next year would hkvt\nto be modified \u201cin the event ol\nprolonged or widespread labor dis\nputes, extensive hoarding (of ma\nterials), serious disruption of the\nprice structure or other unforeseer\ncircumstances.\u2019\u2019\nThe WPB official predicted thai\nby spring unemployment will begir\nto decline, and added that if al\nlowances were made for with\ndrawals from the labor force ol\nwomen, youths returning to school!\nand older persons who will retire\nthen business prospects as he see;\nthem do not \u201cjustify the more pes\nsimistic of the forecasts which havi\nbeen widely publicized\u2014particular\nly the anonymous ones.\u2019\u2019\nProspects are brighter, he said\nfor such products as washing ma\nchines and refrigerators, althougl\nthe total output of these and othei\nconsumer goods \"is dwarfed b;\nthe potential output of the auto\nmobile industry.\u201d\nThe WPB chief hailed the enc\nof widespread shortages of ma\nterials, pointing out that the coun\ntry now has more aluminum ant\nmagnesium \u201cthan we know wha\nto do with\u201d and enough coppei\nand steel to satisfy demand.\nUives overall riciure.\nThis is the picture as given b;\nMr. Krug on other materials:\nLumber\u2014More than enough fo\ncurrent requirements and, with sev\neral months more drying, expectee\nto relieve the seasoned lumbe\nshortage.\nLeather\u2014Plentiful and should b\nreflected \u201cin due course\u201d In in\ncreased quantities of civilian shoes\nRubber\u2014Sufficient for tires for nev\ncars, although it will \u201ctake a littl\ntime\" before replacement needs o\ncars on the road can be met in full\nTextiles\u2014Still short and will tak\nthe industry a \"long time\" to fi]\n1 demand.\nBuilding materials\u2014Very scarce\nf but 'active steps are being take:\nto increase supply.\nPaper\u2014Shortages are being re\nlieved by imports from Sweden, al\ni though newsprint must continue t\nbe restricted to current levels c\nf consumption \u201cfor a little time.\u201d\n1 Navy Draff Calls Reported\nCuf to 1,000 for Novembe\nThe Navy has drastically cut it\ndraft call for November, it was dis\nclosed today by a naval spokesmar\nI who reported that only 1,000 me:\ns will be sought through selectiv\nservice next month.\nThe October call is for 5,000 mer\ni Selective Service is expected to an\ni nounce the reduction soon.\nij The cut was made possible parti\nby 16.000 voluntary enlistments i\nSeptember and 11,800 of them wer\nnew.\nMcPhail Faces Bel Air Hearing\nIn Attack on Phone Workers\nI j By the Associated Press.\nE BEL AIR, Md., Oct. 9.\u2014Larry\nr MacPhail, president of the New\nYork Yankees, is scheduled to ap\npear in Bel Air Police Court next\nTuesday to answer charges of as\nsault and battery and disorderly\ny conduct.\nWarrants against MacPhail were\n3 sworn out by Mrs. Anna Towner,\ns chief operator of the Bel Air Tele\nphone Exchange: Thomas Dwyer,\nmanager of the telephone office,\nand Police Chief Raymond Fulker.\n3 i They al'-ged MacPhail went too far\n3 in complaining that he had not been'\nabie to place a long distance call j\nr from nis showplace, GlenangusI\n3 Fann, near here, during the four\ns hour werk stoppage of phone em- I\n^1 ployes Friday.\ns j MacPhail, who was arrested yes- i\nv terday and posted $554 bond, would\nB not comment.\nChief Fulker said he and the\ncounty sheriff served Mr. MacPhail\nwith warrants containing two\ncharges of assault and battery and\n3 one of disorderly conduct.\n3 Mrs. Towner told newspapermen\nlast night:\n\"The emergency operators and the\nrest of us were all congratulating'\nr mi i i i m\nA'eui Outlook j/OA\nUTILITY\n\u2022STOCKS\ny T 7TILITY Stocks have recently been\n1\u2014/ in the limelight, moving up to a\nA new high for the bull market. This gain\n_ was made in the face of an 11% de\nn cline in electric power output. What are\nthe factors behind current strength? Are\nstill higher prices likely for Utility is\n_ sues? Current UNITED Report ap\nn praises the position and outlook for this\nimportant industry and gives specific ad\nI vice on leading Utility Stocks.\n9 Stocks Favored\nAnalyses and chart studies on 12 promi\nnent Utility issues appear in this report.\n1 Nine of these are singled out as most\nattractive\u2014four for appreciation; five\nfor income.\nYon may have a copy of this im\nportant report withont obligation.\nSend for Bulletin WA-92 Free!\nUnited Business Service\nI *6Unfa*St\nA\nourselves on getting through with\nout trouble springing up.\n\u201cThen that man came in,\u201d sh\nexclaimed, \"and my, oh my.\u201d\nMrs. Towner\u2019s complaint charge\nassault and battery, as did the com\nplaint of Thomas Dwyer, manage\nof the office.\nMr. Fulker was the complainin\nwitness on the disorderly condui\ncharge.\nSeveral hours before the incider\nin the telephone office Mr. Mac\nPhail had played host to 300 agri\nculturists who were making-a tot\nof the section during a Harfor\nCounty \"agriculture conservatio\nfield day.\u201d\nHe lectured on modern method\nused on his farm, where prize-win\nning Angus cattle are raisei\nAmong the visitors were Lou:\nBromfield, author and Ohio farme\nMaryland and Government farm oi\nficials and many of his Harfor\nCounty neighbors.\nNew Yorkers Acclaim\nAdmiral Nimitz With\nParade and Reception\nB\u00bb the Associatefi Freta. I\nNEW YORK, Oct. 9.\u2014Admiral\nChester W. Nimitz came to New\nYork today to receive the city\u2019s first\nofficial reception for a naval hero in\nnearly half a century.\nHe stepped from a silver-painted\nNavy R-5-D at La Guardia Field at\n11:05 a.m., after a flight from Wash\nington, to begin a day-long round\nof activities, including a triumphal\n22-mile tour through crowded\nstreets. It was the first full military\nparade in New York since the start\nof the war.\nEight sideboys piped the admiral\noff the plane in the same fashion\nthat an admiral is traditionally\npiped over the side when he visits\na warship.\nThe Pacific hero, accompanied by\nhis wife and 13 veterans who won\nthe Congressional Medal of Honor\nunder his command, were greeted\nofficially by Mayor F. H. La Guardia,\nAdmiral Jonas Ingram, commander\nin chief of the Atlantic Fleet, and\nother high Navy and Army officers.\nMrs. Nimitz was welcomed by her\nson, Comdr. Chester W. Nimitz, jr.,\nwho nad been standing on the side\nlines to \u201cobserve and enjoy my fa\nther\u2019s discomfort.\u201d\nA 21-piece band struck up \"The\nAdmiral\u2019s March\u201d as Admiral Nimitz\nwalked from his plane to review a\nguard of honor.\nThen, entering an automobile\nwith Mayor La Guardia, he left the\nfield at the head of a motorcade.\nThe first scheduled stop was City\n;Hall, for a ceremony making him\nan honorary citizen of New York.\nTonight he will be feted at a dinner,\nwhere his addiess will be broadcast.\nA cold wind was sweeping the East\nRiver and the crowds along the\nFranklin D. Roosevelt drive from the\nTriborough Bridge were smaller\nthan those on hand for the previous\nwelcomes for Gen. Dwight D. Eisen\nhower and Gen. Jonathan M. Wain\nwright.\nA paper shower began raining\ndown on the motorcade in lower\nManhattan. Prolonged cheers rose\nfrom thousands of persons packed\non sidewalks in that area.\nSwedish Air Force Chief\nTo Arrive Here Tomorrow\nj Lt. Gen. Bengt G. son Norden\nskiold, commander in chief of the\nRoyal Swedish Air Force, will place\na wreath on the Tomb of the Un\nknown Soldier at Arlington at 3;30\np.m. tomorrow.\nThe general has been on a month's\ntrip inspecting United States air\nbases and the aircraft industry as\na guest of the Army Air Forces.\nThe wreath will be placed in the\nname of the Swedish government\nand the Royal Swedish Air Force.\nGen. Nordenskiold will arrive at Na\ntional Airport tomorrow afternoon.\nBrig. Gen. E. J. Timberlake, for\nme- chief of staff of the 8th Aii\nf Force in England, has been conduct\ning the general on his tour.\nd\nr\n8 1\nt It s so important to keep you? smili\nattractive your dentures as spark\nt ling clean as the day you got them\nIt\u2019s easy, too, with STERA-KLEEN\nO'1*' Vi teas- in Vi glass of water\nr soak plate 15 mins, or longer). Usc<\nd daily, STERA-KLEEN helps to keej\nn mucin-scibn, food or tobacco stain\nfrom forming. Checks bad demur*\ns breath. Your FALSE TEETH stay reW/j\nclean more natural-looking! 30f ai\nI. any drug store.\ns\n\nd _\na LUCKY TIGER RUB for\nXcaMmmh\nTry a brisk, refreshing massage with LUCKY\nTIGER Regular. Enjoy the soothing relief it\ngives an itchy scalp caused by loose dandruff\nand miner scalp irritations. Makes your scalp\nfeel better your hair look better. Ask your\nbarber for.a LUCKY TIGER Rub, or\nbottle from your druggist TODAY.\nUICKY TI6\n\u2014\u2014I---p--\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\n\ni i\nFleetCarrying56,300Veterans\nTurns Northward From Canal\nBy JERRY O\u2019LEARY, Jr.,\nStar Staff Carr\nBALBOA, Canal Zone, Oct. 9.\u2014\nThe first large-scale movement of\nships and men from the Pacific\nturned for home today as units of\nVice Admiral Frederick C. Sher\nman\u2019s Task Force 11, carrying 56,300\nsoldier and sailor veterans, moved\nnorthward toward 15 eastern ports\nafter passing through the Panama\nCanal.\nThe fleet, bearing 13,900 Army and\nNavy passengers to separation cen\nters for point release plus 42,400\ncrewmen, consists of 7 carriers, 6\nbattlewagons, 4 cruisers and 30 de\nstroyers.\nAt a press conference aboard the\ncarrier Enterprise yesterday Admiral\nSherman said the armada started\nfrom Tokyo Bay on September 6\nand picked up units from Okinawa\nand Pearl Harbor. Other units\njoined them two days ago from the\nwest coast port*.\nSome passengers aboard are\nwounded. All will disembark for\nseparation centers before the ships\nproceed to assigned ports to partici\npate in Navy Day ceremonies.\nLiDerty m uaiDoa.\nWith 18 ships already through the\ncanal,\u2018the destroyers Pox, Mullany,\nKendrick, Young and Zellars were\nto go through today. On Thurs\nday, the Ranger, North Carolina,\nEnterprise, Washington, Idaho and\ntwo destroyers will pass through.\nThe Randolph will arrive Sunday\nwith the Missouri and the New\nYork.\nMeanwhile, 8,000 liberty-starved\nsailors from Admiral Sherman\u2019s\nfleet swarmed into Balboa, Canal\nZone, and Ciudad de Panama, cap\nital of the republic, for seven hours\nleave. For some this was the first\nsight of civilization in many\nmonths. They eagerly bought\nshawls, alligator handbags, rum\nMarracas and other souvenirs.\nAdmiral Sherman said the atomic\nbomb will Increase the striking\npower of carriers and make them\nmore valuable than they are now\nThe atomic bomb is an airborne\nweapon and the Navy is the best\ndefense against atom bombs, be\ncause with carriers the defense and\noffensive may be projected from the\nI homeland, the admiral said. He\n1 was wearing three Navy Crosses and\nthe Distinguished Service Medal.\nWilling to Take Desk Job.\nThe genial admiral said he was\nwilling to take a desk job after six\nyears at sea. He held the conference\nin the wardroom of the Enterprise\nfightingest ship in the fleet. It ac\ncounted for 911 Japanese planes, 71\nenemy ships and 192 ships damaged\nor probably sunk. The Enterprise\ncollected 18 of a possible 22 battle\nstars for carriers in steaming 275,\n000 miles in pursuit of the foe.\nSome of the best known men-of\nwar of the American Navy are now\nanchored off humid Panama Isth\nmus. Among them are the fast carr\nrier Wasp, whose pilots shot down\nthe last two Japs on August 15, cease\nfire day; the old Battleship New\nMexico, which was struck by kami\nkazes three times; the light carrier\nMonterey, whose planes participated\nin sinking five Jap warships with\nBtrikes against 300 shore-based tar\ngets; the battleship North Carolina,\nreported sunk six times, which par\nticipated in 50 actions, and the light\ncarrier Bataan, whose airmen shot\ndown 129 planes in combat, de\nstroyed 112 on the ground, made 142\nstrikes and sank or damaged 41,500\ntons of merchant shipping.\nWashingtonian Staff Chief.\nChief 6f staff of the task fore*\nwith Admiral Sherman is Capt. M\nE. Curtis of 3626 Windom placi\nN.W., Washington, D. C., who ai\ncaptain of the cruiser Columbli\nfought at Peleliu, Leyte, Mindoro\nLingayen, Borneo and in the bat'\ntie of Leyte Gulf. He was at Pear\nHarbor when the Japs attacked ant\nattended the Jap surrender aboan\nthe Missouri in Tokyo Bay.\nCapt. Herbert D. Riley of Balti\nmore, operations officer of the tasl\nforce, was commanding officer o\nthe escort carrier Makassar Strai\nat Okinawa and Iwo Jima.\nThe intelligence officer is Capt\nJohn C. Broach of Annapolis, Md\nHe is a former submarine office\nand holder of the Silver Star am\nNavy Cross.\nFifty-five United States newspa\ni permen flew to Panama Saturday t<\nimeet the fleet.\n_\nAttilio Piccirilli Dies;\nSculptor, Art Teacher\nBj thf Associated Press.\nNEW YORK. Oct. 9.\u2014Attili\nPiccirilli, 77, sculptor who foundei\nthe Leonardo da Vinci Art Schoc\nand former president of the Amer\nican Italian Art Association, diei\nyesterday. Bogi in Italy, he cami\nto the United States in 1888.\nAmong his works were the Mac\nDonough Monument in New Or\nleans and a bust of Thomas Jef\nferson in the State Capitol at Rich\nmond, Va. He also executed medal\nlions and doors for buildings hen\nand a frieze at the Marconi monu\nment in Washington.\nAgricultural shows in England ar\nresuming and attracting recori\nl crowds.\nPaper Salvage Increased\nTo 19,989,700 Pounds\nSix schools averaging more than\n3,416 pounds of waste paper turned\nin 20,500 pounds yesterday to bring\nthe total of The Evening Star-PTA,\nsalvage program to 19,989,700 pounds.\nThe six schools and their total*\nwere: Jefferson, 1,430; Randall\nJunior, 6,139; Bryan, 556; Buchanan,\n5,442; Orr, 5,900, and Kimball, 2,201.\nCollections in the third district\ntomorrow together with the leader*\nwill be as follows:\nShepherd 31,807 pounds\nTakoma Park.__ 23,297 pounds\nGage...11,641 pounds\nWest..\u2014 10,968 pounds\nAdams 10,224 pounds\nBanneker Macfarland\nH. D. Cooke Bruce\nMilitary Road Monroe\nMorgan Mott\nPark View Pet worth\nW. B. Powell Raymond\nSumner-Magruder H. Wilson\nSeal Campaign Committee\nEnlarges Membership\nAdditional members of the Citl\ni zens\u2019 Committee of the District Tu\nberculosis Association\u2019s 1945 Christ\n1 mas seal campaign have been an\n1 nounced today by Paul D. Sleeper,\n1 chairman.\nVice chairmen appointed were\nRobert H. Davidson, press repre\nsentative of the Chesapeake <fe Po\ntomac Telephone Co., special gifts;\nt E. C. Giddings, assistant to the pres\nident, Capital Transit Co., publicity;\nMrs. Tillman Parks, president of\nthe Federation of Women\u2019s Clubs,\nspeakers\u2019 bureau; Mrs. Charles H.\nI Pierce, depar